  "chunk_index": 26,
  "summary": "After nearly fainting on the grass, Jack Hattersley engages in a conversation with the man who assisted him, Ravelton (also referred to as Laventon or Raffles). Ravelton identifies himself not as a medical doctor, but as a \"soul doctor.\" When Jack expresses his distress and fears he is going insane because he hears voices that others cannot, Ravelton rejects the notion of madness. He compares Jack's experience to the observation of celestial bodies like Jupiter, suggesting that Jack may be a \"signal receiver\" capable of sensing natural phenomena that are invisible to others.\n\nRavelton analyzes the timing of the screams by comparing Jack's watch to his own, confirming that the auditory phenomenon occurs consistently at 7:25. He concludes that the sound is tied to a specific time and location at the villa rather than being a psychological delusion, positing that the phenomenon is governed by natural laws.\n\nLater that evening, Ravelton shares his research regarding the history of Heather House. He explains that the villa was previously owned by the Turners, an English man and a woman of Russian descent who lived in isolation before suddenly departing one morning. While Mr. Turner was seen leaving, no one witnessed Mrs. Turner depart. The property subsequently passed to M. Maurier and was later rented to a French professor and his daughter. Ravelton suggests that the influence of those who die tragically can be absorbed by an environment and transmitted to a suitable receiver like Jack.",
